    <diylc.misc.Label>
      <id>96c8d0d8-838f-4a0c-90fa-464179456e41</id>
      <name>LAB1</name>
      <point x="1.1" y="4.4"/>
      <text>Notes:&lt;br&gt;- Choose Q1 for optimal noise. VR1 can compensate for the noise being too quiet, so focus on flatness!&lt;br&gt;  All but one of the BC547s I tested started to roll off hard around 3kHz - 5kHz as if they were being low-passed,&lt;br&gt;  but every BC337 I tested was nice and flat up to ~12kHz and had only rolled off by ~2dB at 20kHz.&lt;br&gt;- R4 is significantly higher than in (most) other designs as I found that the lower the current going into Q1 was,&lt;br&gt;  the flatter its noise output would be. I&apos;d advise experimenting with this yourself.&lt;br&gt;- C10 is also much higher than the MFOS design I was referencing for the noise amplification circuit as&lt;br&gt;  the 100nF cap used there was causing the noise to get bass boosted...? Not sure why,&lt;br&gt;- The grainy noise comparator circuit seems to clip a lot, and the output likes stay high or low for a few ms at a time.&lt;br&gt;  I&apos;m not sure why but suspect it&apos;s due to different noise characteristics between transistors?</text>
      <font name="Dialog.plain" size="14" style="0"/>
      <color hex="000000"/>
      <horizontalAlignment>LEFT</horizontalAlignment>
      <verticalAlignment>CENTER</verticalAlignment>
      <orientation>DEFAULT</orientation>
    </diylc.misc.Label>
    <diylc.misc.Label>
